description:
Diversity in the ACTPS workforce from June 2012

The ACTPS continues to encourage voluntary disclosure by employees. Diversity percentages are based on total ACTPS headcount which assumes that all respondents do not identify as one or more of the diversity groups, which is likely to result in under-reporting of the actual proportion of diversity groups in the ACTPS.  
Diversity statistics are also provided in Annual Reports and monitored through the ACTPS Respect, Equity and Diversity Framework.  Workforce data in this section has been presented in a way that protects the identity of individual employees. 

Note on Averages: Salary averages here are inclusive of part-time and casual employees. 

Please see the attached document for additional notes.

[State of the Service 2012]

Creative Commons Attribution 3.0 Australia
Chief Minister and Cabinet
http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/au/deed.en
title: Diversity in the ACTPS workforce [State of the Service 2012]

description:
Contract Register, Updated Monthly in this Dataset

Which contracts are registered in the Government Contracts Register?     

In accordance with the Government Procurement Act 2001, from 1 July 2012 (R17) ACT Government contracts with a value of $25,000 or above are publicly viewable on the Government Contracts Register. 

How do I view contracts within the Government Contracts Register?

Using the 'Previous  ACT Government Contracts Register (July 2003 - July 2009)' link, contracts which were loaded onto the previous contract register may be viewed and searched. 

Using the 'New  ACT Government Contracts Register' link, contracts loaded from the 1 August 2009 can be viewed and searched.

Who do I contact regarding specific contracts within the Government Contracts Register?

Details of specific contracts can be obtained through the relevant department/agency.  For system related enquiries, please contact SharedServicesProcurement@act.gov.au.

description:
This spread sheet shows all of the State Suburbs for the ACT and the % of the 15-64 year old population  within each Socio-Economic Indexes for Individuals (SEIFI) IRSD group.  The data used to create this information was the same as used in the research paper “Socio-Economic Indexes for Areas: Getting a handle on individual diversity within areas” by Phillip Wise and Rosalynn Mathews. It is advised that this paper is read to further develop an understanding of the concepts and caveats associated with the analytical output contained in the spreadsheet.

Group 1 – Approx. most disadvantage  20% of the 15-64 year old population 
Group 2 – Approx. second most disadvantaged 20% of the 15- 64 population 
Group 3 – Approx. second least disadvantaged 30% of the 15-64 year old population
Group 4 – Approx. least disadvantaged 30% of the 15-64 year old population 

Please also note that not all ACT CDs have been included as their populations are below the ABS population count threshold (<3), those removed are:
- 8013801 in Reid 
- 8012805 in Turner
- 8014302 in Kingston
- 8021701 in Unclassified ACT
- 8010110 in Bonner
- 8023401 in Tharwa
- 8010103 in Unclassified ACT
- 8014305 in Kingston
- 8014803 in Forrest

It should be noted that multiple Compact Discs of data make up this dataset, as a result the data for each suburb is distributed across several discs. This cccounts for the multiple rows of data that appear for each suburb.
license:
Creative Commons Attribution 3.0 Australia
Chief Minister and Cabinet (CMTD) - ACT Government
http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/au/deed.en
title: ACT Socio-economic Index for Individuals (SEIFI) 2011
